'''Richard John Terrile''' (born March 22, 1951 in New York) is a [[Voyager program|Voyager]] scientist who discovered several [[natural satellite|moons]]<ref name="Blunck2009">{{cite book|last=Blunck|first=Jürgen|title=Solar System Moons: Discovery and Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6YGqFZ_RPdQC&pg=PA94|accessdate=27 May 2011|date=2009-07-01|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-540-68852-5|pages=59, 94}}</ref> of [[Saturn]], [[Uranus]], and [[Neptune]]. He works for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.

Terrile is a supporter of the [[simulation hypothesis]], the idea that our reality is a computer-generated [[virtual reality]] created by unknown programmers.<ref name="vice">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/whoa-dude-are-we-inside-a-computer-right-now-0000329-v19n9|title=Whoa, Dude, Are We Inside a Computer Right Now?|author=Ben Makuch|website=Vice.com|date=11 September 2012}}</ref><ref name="ideacity">{{cite web|url=http://www.ideacity.ca/video/richard-terrile-the-universe-as-a-simulation/|title=Richard Terrile – The Universe as a Simulation|author=Richard Terrile|website=Ideacity|date=2015}}</ref>

